title.narrative: Budget and Financial Accountability - Sri Lanka

description.narrative: The Advisor provides technical assistance to the Sri Lankan Ministry of Finance to strengthen public financial management, specifically improvements to treasury operations including improving commitment and cash controls Shoring up the national public finances is one of the highest political priorities of the Government of Sri Lanka. Technical assistance objectives focus on: • Expanding and improving the implementation of the treasury single account (TSA) concept, including expanding the scope of the TSA to include state owned enterprises and other government entities, as appropriate; • Insuring the implementation of enhanced commitment controls within the planned Integrated Treasury Management Information System to reduce the accumulation of arrears and improve internal controls; • Improving the efficiency of treasury operations by streamlining the number of operational bank accounts through the use of centralized payments and other techniques; • Designing and implementing strategies to improve liquidity management such as: implementing new bank arrangements based on competitive bidding, expanding the use of electronic payments, and reducing petty cash through the use of payment card or other innovative payment modalities; • Insuring improved coordination between revenue collecting agencies and treasury; • Developing procedures to insure that the ITMIS is periodically reconciled with internal debt management systems; and • Designing a professional development training program for treasury personnel.. Project has been discontinued.

owner-org.narrative: The federal government of the United States

description.narrative: Twice during 2015, Sri Lankans went to the polls and demanded dramatic political changes in their government - in both the Presidential and Parliamentary elections. These elections changed Sri Lanka's political landscape, offering an opportunity to strengthen U.S.-Sri Lanka relations leading to greater political and economic cooperation and enhanced foreign assistance programming. The United States will support the new Sri Lankan government's reconciliation, reform, and accountability agenda with increased resources and programming to achieve historic advancements in human rights, economic equality, and stability that were inconceivable a year ago. With FY 2017 resources, the United States will partner with civil society to increase accountability and transparency; protect human rights and fundamental freedoms; strengthen rule of law and democratic institutions; increase security and stability; promote reconciliation, interfaith harmony, and inter-ethnic understanding; and bolster good governance and economic growth.
